1
00:00:01,550 --> 00:00:10,342
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah.

2
00:00:12,926 --> 00:00:21,937
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasah.

3
00:00:25,309 --> 00:00:42,031
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhassa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

4
00:00:47,118 --> 00:00:52,244
Yesterday we tackled some of the worst hindrances we come across in meditation.

5
00:00:52,781 --> 00:00:55,448
All hindrances, of course, are as bad as one another.

6
00:00:56,731 --> 00:01:05,109
The fact is, every one of us has their own peculiar constellation, and there'll always be one or two that hang on till the end of time.

7
00:01:05,150 --> 00:01:11,584
Time governed by the self ends, of course, only with the fully awakened being.

8
00:01:12,813 --> 00:01:23,679
However, what we find is that in vipassana, although they are called hindrances, once they become objects to observe, they unwittingly become aids to our liberation.

9
00:01:24,521 --> 00:01:30,534
For by watching the hindrances do we come to understand how suffering arises and how it passes away.

10
00:01:32,641 --> 00:01:37,566
This evening we're going to look at the brighter side of meditation, the factors of enlightenment.

11
00:01:38,587 --> 00:01:43,674
And we're going to start with a guided meditation so that you can actually experience these factors.

12
00:01:45,256 --> 00:01:48,438
None of them, unfortunately, are wow experiences.

13
00:01:49,159 --> 00:01:59,171
They are really quite ordinary states, heightened, no doubt, and directed at a certain investigation, that investigation of our interior life.

14
00:02:00,670 --> 00:02:11,693
So as always, start with the body, energize the spine, get everything to relax and feel comfortable.

15
00:02:30,067 --> 00:02:33,191
Settling now on the feeling of the breath in the abdomen.

16
00:02:33,931 --> 00:02:35,193
Get in contact with it.

17
00:02:36,253 --> 00:02:37,695
Just observe and note it.

18
00:02:38,776 --> 00:02:39,397
Rising.

19
00:02:40,560 --> 00:02:41,199
Falling.

20
00:02:42,762 --> 00:02:43,242
Touching.

21
00:02:47,527 --> 00:02:48,288
But feel it.

22
00:02:48,930 --> 00:02:50,070
What does it feel like?

23
00:02:51,612 --> 00:02:53,895
How would you describe the feeling of it?

24
00:02:55,497 --> 00:02:59,382
Hopefully you'll say something like calm, gentle, soft, deep.

25
00:03:00,795 --> 00:03:03,260
If so, feel it, acknowledge it.

26
00:03:06,168 --> 00:03:09,835
But it could also be tight, coarse, short, unrelaxed.

27
00:03:10,336 --> 00:03:14,264
If so, just feel it, acknowledge it.

28
00:03:16,625 --> 00:03:20,771
Recognising these qualities is the factor of awareness, that knowing.

29
00:03:22,014 --> 00:03:32,030
Stay with these feelings now for a while, and of course, should the mind wander, well, just note it, what it's getting caught up in, and return to the breath.

30
00:03:34,775 --> 00:03:39,763
Rising Falling Touching

31
00:05:41,682 --> 00:05:43,906
Can you feel the calmness of the breath?

32
00:05:45,208 --> 00:05:49,475
Or, if it has been tight or agitated, that it's getting calmer?

33
00:05:51,617 --> 00:05:53,201
This is the quality of calmness.

34
00:05:54,322 --> 00:06:01,834
Perhaps you sense, surrounding these calm sensations, a general feeling of composure, even serenity.

35
00:06:03,437 --> 00:06:06,002
This is all the factor of tranquillity.

36
00:06:07,619 --> 00:06:13,910
It manifests as calmness in the heart, quietness in the mind and stillness in the body.

37
00:06:17,055 --> 00:06:19,901
Become aware of this general tranquility.

38
00:06:21,564 --> 00:06:24,649
Use a noting word such as calm, tranquil.

39
00:08:25,774 --> 00:08:29,257
Now the danger here is that we develop this state for itself.

40
00:08:30,439 --> 00:08:33,501
There's nothing to be gained from this on the road to liberation.

41
00:08:34,763 --> 00:08:41,149
So we must now bring in another quality to balance it, and that is interest.

42
00:08:41,168 --> 00:08:47,274
Let's raise the interest to see more clearly, more precisely, what this process of breathing entails.

43
00:08:48,817 --> 00:08:52,440
Let's see if we can distinguish some of the four great elements.

44
00:08:54,158 --> 00:09:06,796
can we become more aware of the quality of movement, the air element, or a gentle pressure, the earth element, or maybe there are feelings of warmth or coolness, the fire element.

45
00:09:08,238 --> 00:09:12,764
We might even feel a certain elasticity in the movement, the water element.

46
00:09:14,827 --> 00:09:17,751
Use a noting word that you find most appropriate.

47
00:09:18,352 --> 00:09:20,436
It doesn't matter what you're aware of.

48
00:09:22,356 --> 00:09:25,025
Raise that interest to investigate.

49
00:11:26,523 --> 00:11:33,772
Within the calmness and interest, we may have noticed a greater degree of focus and rise in our energy level.

50
00:11:35,253 --> 00:11:39,558
Let's reinforce this now by bringing in a deeper investigation of the Dharma.

51
00:11:41,380 --> 00:11:45,105
In the breath, we can become more aware of the quality of impermanence.

52
00:11:46,427 --> 00:11:50,792
But approach the breath in the position of don't know or not sure.

53
00:11:51,615 --> 00:11:58,581
This means there's no preconceptions in the mind, no prejudice, no expectations, no emotional distortions.

54
00:11:58,903 --> 00:12:01,345
This is the quality of equanimity.

55
00:12:02,885 --> 00:12:05,369
We need this to clarify our investigation.

56
00:12:07,250 --> 00:12:09,471
So let's look a little more keenly, more deeply.

57
00:12:10,293 --> 00:12:11,774
How transient is the breath?

58
00:12:12,595 --> 00:12:16,339
Is the breath one thing, or is it made up of little segments?

59
00:12:17,559 --> 00:12:19,041
How small are these segments?

60
00:12:19,797 --> 00:12:23,844
To begin to see this, we need to be right there when the in-breath begins.

61
00:12:24,765 --> 00:12:27,791
Stay with the sensations all the way to the very end.

62
00:12:28,972 --> 00:12:29,975
Same with the out-breath.

63
00:12:30,956 --> 00:12:36,687
And in the pause, if we are still not steady, then turn our attention onto a touch point.

64
00:12:38,129 --> 00:12:41,534
But better if we can stay right there where we feel the breath.

65
00:14:42,913 --> 00:14:51,403
It may be that as you raise the interest to see the quality of transience, the quality of calmness has diminished and you find yourself getting tight.

66
00:14:52,625 --> 00:14:56,870
If so, back off for a minute and feel the calmness in the breath.

67
00:14:58,932 --> 00:15:01,375
Go back for a while to the beginning of the exercise.

68
00:15:03,317 --> 00:15:07,062
Once there's tranquility re-established, restart the investigation.

69
00:15:08,442 --> 00:15:12,447
Remind yourself that all we have to do is to watch and observe

70
00:15:13,693 --> 00:15:15,879
We're not trying to see something.

71
00:15:16,402 --> 00:15:18,226
We're not looking for something.

72
00:15:19,009 --> 00:15:23,181
We're just looking at what we are feeling and experiencing.

73
00:17:24,491 --> 00:17:33,865
As we raised the desire to investigate, so the feeling of interest arose, and with it we were able to focus down, as it were, into the breath.

74
00:17:35,528 --> 00:17:44,981
That's another factor, focusing or concentration, being able to be still, to put the attention still on the object.

75
00:17:46,503 --> 00:17:49,268
And the only effort you need is to keep it still.

76
00:17:50,497 --> 00:17:53,040
This effort is another of the seven factors.

77
00:17:54,021 --> 00:18:01,932
It's a gentle but constant flow of energy supporting the interest, not the wish to become concentrated.

78
00:18:03,695 --> 00:18:10,464
The only effort needed is just to sharpen the looking, that's the focus, and to hold it there, steady.

79
00:18:12,667 --> 00:18:18,916
Let the strength of the attention grow of its own accord because of our interest to investigate the Dharma.

80
00:18:20,652 --> 00:18:26,864
Let our intention be simply to see, to feel the sensations, feel the feelings of the breath.

81
00:18:29,367 --> 00:18:39,807
So now, let's begin again and focus in so that we can become more and more aware of the subtler feelings of the breath, the simple sensations.

82
00:18:40,902 --> 00:18:49,443
Get into the texture, their softness, perhaps a liquid quality, perhaps warmth, the movement, the ebb and flow, like the sway of the sea.

83
00:18:50,768 --> 00:18:53,915
The rise and fall of the in-breath and the out-breath.

84
00:20:55,227 --> 00:21:05,156
So here we are, the body with its energized spine, everything relaxed, manifesting these two factors of effort and tranquility.

85
00:21:06,397 --> 00:21:12,565
The breath breathing softly, awareness, the knowing, noting, watching, feeling.

86
00:21:13,746 --> 00:21:19,951
The interest held in balance with tranquility rises to investigate the Dharma.

87
00:21:19,932 --> 00:21:29,705
held objectively by equanimity, and the focus coming naturally, and the effort too, raised by our desire to know.

88
00:21:31,888 --> 00:21:37,778
So, now that all the factors are there, let's forget all the instructions and everything we've heard.

89
00:21:38,659 --> 00:21:45,028
Let's just note and watch, feel and observe, investigate and examine.

90
00:23:47,538 --> 00:23:53,083
So now we have an inkling of this other side of the equation, opposed to all the hindrances.

91
00:23:54,184 --> 00:23:59,609
These are the wonderful faculties and qualities we have, even if they do need a little developing.

92
00:24:01,751 --> 00:24:06,115
I want to add to these seven factors of enlightenment the spiritual faculties.

93
00:24:07,518 --> 00:24:16,026
The faculties, the indriya, are faith, energy, awareness, concentration and wisdom.

94
00:24:16,883 --> 00:24:30,203
And the factors of enlightenment, the bhojanga, are awareness, investigation of the Dharma, effort, interest, tranquility, concentration and equanimity.

95
00:24:33,008 --> 00:24:38,798
I'm going to try and dovetail them so that you get an overall perspective of what we need to develop.

96
00:24:40,681 --> 00:24:44,105
The first and ground of all spiritual qualities is faith.

97
00:24:45,250 --> 00:24:49,455
Faith here is not to be confused with belief.

98
00:24:49,476 --> 00:25:04,516
If what we mean by belief is an unqualified certainty in a statement, for instance, if I say, I believe in the teachings of the Buddha, there's a danger that I'll never question them, never want to really find out if they're true for me.

99
00:25:04,576 --> 00:25:08,361
I bask in the warm comfort of my belief.

100
00:25:09,722 --> 00:25:11,023
It can lead to gullibility.

101
00:25:11,744 --> 00:25:15,190
We'll believe anything the Buddha said just because he said it.

102
00:25:16,654 --> 00:25:24,250
It develops an intellectual deadness, emotional blindness, blind faith, and so on to fundamentalism.

103
00:25:26,213 --> 00:25:35,692
No, what the Buddha meant by sadha was confidence, putting one's trust in, in the same way that we may trust a doctor or a dentist.

104
00:25:37,681 --> 00:25:47,712
Faith is a trust which still allows an open, enquiring mind, and that leads to commitment and then to action, to taking the necessary steps.

105
00:25:49,234 --> 00:25:58,306
There was the case of Sariputta, the person whom the Buddha had called the General of the Dharma, recognising him as second only to himself in understanding.

106
00:25:59,768 --> 00:26:03,772
Sariputta declared that the Buddha was the most enlightened being ever,

107
00:26:04,984 --> 00:26:07,106
The Buddha asked him how he knew.

108
00:26:07,146 --> 00:26:10,171
Now no doubt Sariputta was taken aback a little.

109
00:26:11,432 --> 00:26:17,699
He then explained he had come to intuit this from his own standpoint as a fully liberated being himself.

110
00:26:20,301 --> 00:26:31,734
Yesterday we spoke of sceptical doubt, how this can become an insidious spiritual disease, a mental habit that stops us trusting, stops us committing and so acting.

111
00:26:33,435 --> 00:26:35,278
We saw how the reasons can be varied.

112
00:26:36,359 --> 00:26:37,780
It may be fear of commitment.

113
00:26:38,761 --> 00:26:42,727
Perhaps trust has been betrayed, so that we can't even trust ourselves.

114
00:26:44,068 --> 00:26:48,213
Or perhaps an underlying, unacknowledged aversion to religion, or whatever.

115
00:26:49,736 --> 00:26:54,942
Usually the person is unaware of the reason, and they justify, rationalize their doubt.

116
00:26:56,403 --> 00:27:01,569
They question and discuss only to prove the other wrong, and so justify their position.

117
00:27:03,102 --> 00:27:05,905
But the fact is, they never commit themselves to any path.

118
00:27:06,907 --> 00:27:11,756
And spiritually, their lives remain arid, infertile and unproductive.

119
00:27:13,699 --> 00:27:16,383
As we have seen, sceptical doubt takes three forms.

120
00:27:16,824 --> 00:27:21,451
Doubt in the Buddha and his teachings, doubt in the teacher and doubt in oneself.

121
00:27:23,394 --> 00:27:30,105
It does happen that a person begins to doubt the teachings, not only those born into the religion, but even converts.

122
00:27:31,097 --> 00:27:34,921
I know of someone who decided after many years that Hinduism was for her.

123
00:27:36,363 --> 00:27:39,325
If she had said just that, well, that would have been understandable.

124
00:27:39,786 --> 00:27:41,907
Each of us is drawn in different ways.

125
00:27:43,469 --> 00:27:49,253
But she went on to say that Hinduism was a more advanced religion and that Buddhism only took you so far.

126
00:27:50,154 --> 00:27:51,916
Well, that's another matter altogether.

127
00:27:53,417 --> 00:28:00,243
And such a statement tells us more about her practice and doubt than anything about the relationship between Buddhism and Hinduism.

128
00:28:02,012 --> 00:28:09,884
It's often true that we join a spiritual path with great expectations, some conceptual idea of what enlightenment is, for instance.

129
00:28:11,006 --> 00:28:15,151
And if these are not fulfilled, we can presume there's something wrong with the religion.

130
00:28:16,693 --> 00:28:20,778
I don't know what happened to her, but I wouldn't be surprised if she hasn't moved on again.

131
00:28:22,902 --> 00:28:27,008
So faith is the ability to trust, but not without discrimination.

132
00:28:28,490 --> 00:28:31,934
So how do we arrive at this confidence in the first place?

133
00:28:32,287 --> 00:28:36,071
Well, by pañña, wisdom, not one's own, but the wisdom of others.

134
00:28:37,313 --> 00:28:41,598
We come to hear the teachings of the Buddha, and we awaken, as it were, to the truth.

135
00:28:43,601 --> 00:28:46,724
Faith begins then with some degree of intellectual agreement.

136
00:28:47,746 --> 00:28:50,529
It awakens in us some desire for spiritual knowledge.

137
00:28:51,771 --> 00:28:54,234
Wonder arises, an honest doubt, as it were.

138
00:28:54,915 --> 00:28:56,116
I wonder if it's true.

139
00:28:57,817 --> 00:29:06,127
such a person begins to think about it, mulling it over, until, by their own intellectual effort, they have made it their own understanding.

140
00:29:06,929 --> 00:29:11,213
But it's still abstract, still conceptual, still stuck in the head.

141
00:29:14,196 --> 00:29:21,025
If that spiritual desire has been truly awakened, it won't just stop there, but go on to investigate in a real way,

142
00:29:22,574 --> 00:29:25,941
they will begin to put into practice what they've come to understand.

143
00:29:27,022 --> 00:29:32,032
And this leads to direct experience to true realization of the way things really are.

144
00:29:33,315 --> 00:29:36,421
Only then is there any real change in the person.

145
00:29:37,563 --> 00:29:41,510
By this time it has become the true wisdom of personal experience.

146
00:29:42,875 --> 00:29:57,273
So it is that through these three degrees of received understanding, to personal intellectual understanding, to experiential understanding, that a person comes to realise the way things really are, as it's put in the scriptures.

147
00:29:58,855 --> 00:30:04,644
And underpinning these three levels is faith, confidence, trust and commitment.

148
00:30:06,967 --> 00:30:08,628
Then there's that doubt in the teacher.

149
00:30:09,807 --> 00:30:17,740
Again, if it's skeptical doubt, based on an habitual inability to trust people, it will be a barrier to following the instructions.

150
00:30:19,563 --> 00:30:27,596
When someone suffers from skeptical doubt towards teachers, they say they can't find one, or they always have good reasons for going to someone else.

151
00:30:28,798 --> 00:30:32,964
There's a fear of being misled, conned, worse, ending up in a pit.

152
00:30:34,547 --> 00:30:36,269
How do we know when to trust someone?

153
00:30:37,886 --> 00:30:41,392
Well, this is one of the advantages of working within a tradition.

154
00:30:42,773 --> 00:30:52,868
Buddhism, like all world religions, has a long history and many witnesses, both ancient and present, who testify to the validity and effectiveness of the Buddha's teachings.

155
00:30:55,073 --> 00:31:05,228
Secondly, the teacher in a particular meditative tradition, such as the Mahasi tradition, will have teachers themselves who have authorised, approved or encouraged them to teach.

156
00:31:06,592 --> 00:31:17,808
And thirdly, because there are other teachers in that tradition, a meditator can always attend their courses, and by way of comparison feel assured they're getting the teachings of that tradition.

157
00:31:19,332 --> 00:31:24,799
But we shouldn't forget that there are honest doubts, and these ought to be cleared up as quickly as possible.

158
00:31:26,923 --> 00:31:33,814
There's also great danger at the other end of the scale, blind faith in a teacher, the my guru infatuation.

159
00:31:35,313 --> 00:31:39,179
There was a tale I heard told of Ajahn Chah, a famous Thai teacher.

160
00:31:40,320 --> 00:31:45,208
He went off to spend time with someone who had got the reputation of being fully enlightened.

161
00:31:46,630 --> 00:31:48,874
After a time, he became fairly convinced.

162
00:31:49,413 --> 00:31:54,481
But then one day, he happened to catch his teacher angrily giving a dog a great kick.

163
00:31:55,784 --> 00:32:01,573
Now, if you've been to Thai monasteries and suffered the packs of dogs, believe me, you'd have a lot of sympathy for that monk.

164
00:32:02,869 --> 00:32:08,336
It seems the dog had got to a choice piece of meat left by a supporter for the monks.

165
00:32:08,355 --> 00:32:16,226
Anyway, such anger didn't tally with the concept of Arahat, the fully enlightened being, liberated from greed, hatred and delusion.

166
00:32:17,106 --> 00:32:18,769
So it seems Ajahn Chah left.

167
00:32:19,789 --> 00:32:20,971
So, be aware.

168
00:32:21,010 --> 00:32:32,505
It's always a disappointment to find out that your teacher is not quite the fully enlightened being you thought they were, and that occasionally they can be as stupid as yourself.

169
00:32:33,615 --> 00:32:40,903
Mind you, I think it's only natural to put our teachers on a pedestal and feel you have a right to some sort of special intimacy with them.

170
00:32:42,144 --> 00:32:43,006
I've certainly done it.

171
00:32:44,186 --> 00:32:48,751
I remember I once smiled upon my teacher with that loving devotion of a devotee.

172
00:32:50,053 --> 00:32:52,015
To my hurt surprise, he turned away.

173
00:32:52,035 --> 00:32:54,217
I still didn't get the message.

174
00:32:55,337 --> 00:33:01,664
I placed my seat in front of his in the shrine room, and when I returned, he'd moved his to the other side of the shrine.

175
00:33:03,333 --> 00:33:07,378
I shall always be grateful to him for his gentle refusal to play guru.

176
00:33:09,482 --> 00:33:19,136
Now there are people who form such intimate relationships of dependency that even when they're shown proof of criminality, believe it's been a set-up.

177
00:33:19,157 --> 00:33:20,680
Of course the guru knows what he's doing.

178
00:33:22,001 --> 00:33:25,446
This is not to say that the guru-teacher relationships cannot work.

179
00:33:26,388 --> 00:33:31,737
However, the Buddha himself discouraged any feelings of attachment to him, turning him into a guru.

180
00:33:32,999 --> 00:33:38,278
There was the case of a young monk who was obviously swooning of him, so he sent him off to the forest.

181
00:33:39,482 --> 00:33:44,882
That sort of relationship gets in the way of the path of Gnosis, the path of understanding.

182
00:33:46,246 --> 00:33:52,731
The Buddha's path is one of precise self-investigation and severe purification, as you know.

183
00:33:53,992 --> 00:33:56,655
The Buddha is not a guru, but an instructor.

184
00:33:57,757 --> 00:34:01,320
That's why in the Zen tradition, meditators are called trainees.

185
00:34:02,461 --> 00:34:07,906
The relationship of a trainee to the instructor is one of obedience, a word the modern self hates.

186
00:34:08,827 --> 00:34:15,273
Perhaps surrender is easier to understand, or perhaps to follow instructions is easier still.

187
00:34:15,253 --> 00:34:17,056
to follow with discrimination, that is.

188
00:34:18,016 --> 00:34:22,282
In other words, all instructions are to be taken on the basis of trial and error.

189
00:34:23,523 --> 00:34:27,447
Any attachment to the teacher would get in the way of that clear comprehension.

190
00:34:29,449 --> 00:34:37,818
The opposite is true, of course, that the trainee has to see that any aversion towards the instructor is also a loss of impartiality on their part.

191
00:34:39,519 --> 00:34:44,907
The trainee should have no difficulty in questioning the instructions or in constructively criticizing them.

192
00:34:45,887 --> 00:34:49,413
The instructor should not be in authority over the trainee.

193
00:34:50,034 --> 00:34:52,777
That's to do with power and inspires only fear.

194
00:34:53,679 --> 00:34:57,744
They should be an authority for the trainee and inspire respect.

195
00:34:59,425 --> 00:35:05,494
A true willingness to follow the instructions given, not the instructor, should be a consequence of this respect.

196
00:35:07,887 --> 00:35:09,548
Finally, there's doubt in oneself.

197
00:35:10,210 --> 00:35:11,132
Everyone else can do it.

198
00:35:11,391 --> 00:35:11,773
It's me.

199
00:35:12,474 --> 00:35:13,315
I just can't do it.

200
00:35:13,594 --> 00:35:14,777
I'm a born failure.

201
00:35:16,440 --> 00:35:28,157
When that sort of self-hatred, self-pity, self-low esteem, low self-confidence, when any of that sort of stuff arises, don't allow yourself to get caught up in it.

202
00:35:29,824 --> 00:35:40,324
How is it we can't believe the Buddha when he says everyone has the potential to become fully awakened and yet be happily prepared to guide our lives with such self-defeating thoughts?

203
00:35:41,434 --> 00:35:44,239
Okay, so we may not be spiritual geniuses.

204
00:35:44,601 --> 00:35:45,061
So what?

205
00:35:45,864 --> 00:35:47,586
There's no time limit put on this.

206
00:35:48,489 --> 00:35:49,771
We have as long as it will take.

207
00:35:50,773 --> 00:35:54,621
Slowly but surely, we'll advance, step by step.

208
00:35:55,663 --> 00:36:00,572
The path is gradual, and for the vast majority of us, very gradual.

209
00:36:01,614 --> 00:36:02,936
The Buddha warned us.

210
00:36:03,355 --> 00:36:07,422
So for heaven's sake, never put your faith in self-doubt.

211
00:36:07,601 --> 00:36:09,125
Don't believe the voices.

212
00:36:09,987 --> 00:36:19,804
As always, listen, feel, observe, experience and come to understand and affirm our natural human ability.

213
00:36:21,286 --> 00:36:23,811
I am able to become liberated.

214
00:36:24,364 --> 00:36:28,195
I ought to become fully awakened for my own sake and the sake of others.

215
00:36:29,237 --> 00:36:33,750
I want to, and I will become a fully awakened being.

216
00:36:35,637 --> 00:36:38,481
So dealing with doubt is part of growing in faith.

217
00:36:39,262 --> 00:36:46,371
Until with that glimpse of the end of the path, we actually know for sure that the end of suffering is truly attainable.

218
00:36:47,773 --> 00:37:01,711
Upon reaching the first path and fruit, that of sotapanna, stream entry as it is called, this faith, now based upon the direct experience of nibbana, becomes unshakable and is known as a power, bala.

219
00:37:03,277 --> 00:37:07,686
That sort of faith has become a conviction based on personal experience.

220
00:37:09,050 --> 00:37:12,697
No more doubt as to the efficacy of the Buddha's teaching can arise again.

221
00:37:12,737 --> 00:37:20,072
Nor will there be any doubt as to the path leading to the final end of all our struggles.

222
00:37:22,043 --> 00:37:30,719
Now paññā, this faculty of wisdom, which has grown along with faith, the one supporting the other, is an active, intuitive intelligence.

223
00:37:31,599 --> 00:37:40,195
And it is in this mode that it is included in the factors of enlightenment, the investigation of dharma, dhammawicchaya.

224
00:37:40,215 --> 00:37:44,422
Here it needs a further support, and this is equanimity, upekā.

225
00:37:45,331 --> 00:37:54,483
Equanimity is even-mindedness, impartiality and suggests a calmness in the heart and non-attachment to what is going on.

226
00:37:56,106 --> 00:38:01,132
We expect judges to have both the wisdom and the equanimity factors highly developed.

227
00:38:02,514 --> 00:38:08,503
They're supposed to stand above the emotions of the crowd and not be fooled by the clever arguments of the lawyers.

228
00:38:10,188 --> 00:38:19,876
This is the sort of attitude we have to have to all our interior life, if Panya, our intuitive intelligence, is going to see things as they really are.

229
00:38:21,358 --> 00:38:31,648
So equanimity produces that ability to receive, to accept, to acknowledge without fear or favour, not distorted by anger and prejudice.

230
00:38:32,989 --> 00:38:36,532
It is the basic quality of the open heart and clear mind.

231
00:38:39,179 --> 00:38:45,590
Supporting this pair, the heart, our emotional base, has to be both tranquil and yet joyous.

232
00:38:46,851 --> 00:38:52,481
Tranquility, pasadie, is that sense of calm and contentment, a peaceful heart.

233
00:38:54,045 --> 00:38:56,108
Pity here is the joy of interest.

234
00:38:57,230 --> 00:39:01,557
Just think how happy we are when we're doing something we're really interested in.

235
00:39:02,686 --> 00:39:05,829
But the enemy of this spiritual joy is excitement.

236
00:39:06,969 --> 00:39:15,878
And excitement will immediately begin to corrupt the whole process once we've allowed some idea of getting, achieving, attaining to enter the practice.

237
00:39:17,478 --> 00:39:18,860
And that's what tranquility does.

238
00:39:19,641 --> 00:39:22,684
It keeps that joyous interest from becoming excited.

239
00:39:24,264 --> 00:39:32,371
But tranquility also harbours a danger, and that's to draw us into a lovely, floaty, calm state, the land of lotus eaters,

240
00:39:33,465 --> 00:39:36,068
Well, it's all very beautiful, but where's it leading us?

241
00:39:37,490 --> 00:39:49,606
We don't realise where it's leading us till we come out of it, and we find it's leading us nowhere but to an attachment for that sort of impermanent delight, yet another path to unsatisfactoriness.

242
00:39:51,429 --> 00:39:54,112
So again, it's all to do with balance.

243
00:39:54,132 --> 00:39:57,836
We need to develop calmness with a highly engaged interest.

244
00:40:00,061 --> 00:40:06,108
Finally, there's the pair, which are both faculties and factors, effort and concentration.

245
00:40:07,590 --> 00:40:12,998
Concentration is a word which conjures up for us struggle, head down, knitted brow.

246
00:40:14,579 --> 00:40:16,021
Perhaps a better word is focus.

247
00:40:16,903 --> 00:40:19,746
It's the collected mind, a mind unscattered.

248
00:40:21,088 --> 00:40:25,856
It draws all the light in the mind into a laser beam, so to speak.

249
00:40:25,876 --> 00:40:29,139
The energy is simply that needed to bring this about.

250
00:40:30,773 --> 00:40:41,148
If we think of a camera, it can focus, concentrate on something near or far, and the motor which turns the lenses is the energy needed to get the focus we want.

251
00:40:42,630 --> 00:40:44,914
Once we've got the right focus, we can take the picture.

252
00:40:45,715 --> 00:40:49,721
We can note, feel, observe, experience and come to understand.

253
00:40:50,782 --> 00:40:54,148
We can't do it if the focus is fuzzy or intermittent.

254
00:40:55,157 --> 00:41:00,842
We've got to be able to hold that focus, and that's what this pair of concentration and effort do.

255
00:41:03,085 --> 00:41:04,567
Again, they've got to be balanced.

256
00:41:05,547 --> 00:41:11,152
If there's more energy about than is needed, then that extra energy dissipates into restlessness.

257
00:41:12,293 --> 00:41:19,019
If we investigate the reasons for this, we may find the extra energy to be empowered by self-centered desire.

258
00:41:20,141 --> 00:41:23,224
That same old problem of wanting to achieve something,

259
00:41:24,688 --> 00:41:32,443
Adversely, it may be that there's a lack of energy because the self isn't getting what it wants, so it gets bored and fed up.

260
00:41:34,005 --> 00:41:37,954
Whatever, we'll need to spend time calming and re-centering ourselves.

261
00:41:40,137 --> 00:41:47,271
If the concentration is well developed and there's not enough energy to support it, then we fall into a state of unconsciousness.

262
00:41:48,161 --> 00:41:50,106
This isn't the same as sleep as such.

263
00:41:51,027 --> 00:41:55,056
When this happens to a meditator, the body remains quite still in position.

264
00:41:56,498 --> 00:42:02,411
When we're suffering from sloth, as I'm sure you all know, the body bobs up and down and occasionally collapses.

265
00:42:03,492 --> 00:42:08,161
The other sign is that when the meditator wakes up, as it were, they're fully bright.

266
00:42:10,369 --> 00:42:15,114
This combination of focus and effort is well illustrated by the story of Sona.

267
00:42:16,317 --> 00:42:28,289
He knew himself to be one of the disciples exceptional in effort but he became discouraged by the lack of progress in his practice and decided to leave, build up a family and gather lots of good karma.

268
00:42:29,931 --> 00:42:34,856
The Buddha by his supranormal powers came to know what he was thinking and appeared next to him.

269
00:42:36,760 --> 00:42:39,802
He embarrassed poor Sona by telling him what he was thinking of doing

270
00:42:41,284 --> 00:42:44,271
He then asks if he played a wiener as a layperson.

271
00:42:45,835 --> 00:42:50,143
When the strings of your wiener were too taut, was your wiener in tune and playable?

272
00:42:51,065 --> 00:42:52,608
No, Lord, Sona replied.

273
00:42:54,432 --> 00:42:58,601
And when the strings of your wiener were too loose, was your wiener in tune and playable?

274
00:42:59,724 --> 00:43:01,909
No, Lord, Sona replied again.

275
00:43:03,711 --> 00:43:11,945
But when the strings of your vina were neither too taut nor too loose, but tuned at the right pitch, was your vina in tune and playable?

276
00:43:12,666 --> 00:43:13,226
Yes, Lord.

277
00:43:14,730 --> 00:43:18,635
In the same way, Sona, too much energy and effort leads to restlessness.

278
00:43:19,496 --> 00:43:23,103
Overly slack effort and energy leads to laziness.

279
00:43:23,905 --> 00:43:28,572
Therefore, you should determine the right pitch of your energy and effort.

280
00:43:30,086 --> 00:43:37,554
This of course Sona did and in no longer time attained and remained in that supreme goal of the holy life.

281
00:43:39,516 --> 00:43:41,259
So how do we do this?

282
00:43:41,278 --> 00:43:47,326
Well the trick that works for me is to let go of worrying about effort and trying to concentrate.

283
00:43:48,407 --> 00:43:53,512
Instead to draw my energies into raising interest and just watching.

284
00:43:54,742 --> 00:44:01,389
Consider, did you ever have any problems with concentration and effort when you were interested in something?

285
00:44:03,833 --> 00:44:05,875
Finally there is sati, awareness.

286
00:44:07,257 --> 00:44:16,427
Now if there's one word which encapsulates the whole of the Buddha's teachings, at least in terms of the practice, it's got to be this one, sati, awareness.

287
00:44:18,090 --> 00:44:24,478
The establishing of this level of consciousness as a constant is the path to enlightenment.

288
00:44:25,706 --> 00:44:32,516
Indeed, to establish right awareness for one moment is to be awakened in that moment, though not fully mind.

289
00:44:33,777 --> 00:44:43,230
This, in fact, is all we're trying to do throughout this course, to put ourselves into samasati, helped by whatever technique possible, and to try to maintain it.

290
00:44:45,512 --> 00:44:50,820
In Vipassana Guidelines, I've brought together various definitions that other teachers use.

291
00:44:52,387 --> 00:45:00,498
I can't remember now where I got them all from, but for me they come as close as you can get with words to describe what sati is.

292
00:45:00,538 --> 00:45:07,568
It is a bare attentiveness, simply watching all that arises and passes away.

293
00:45:09,411 --> 00:45:11,914
Now this is shorthand for the three characteristics.

294
00:45:12,996 --> 00:45:18,023
Impermanence is only one of them, and perhaps the most obvious to most people.

295
00:45:18,188 --> 00:45:31,128
But as we observe the transient nature of all phenomena we also come to see how suffering arises and passes away and how the self, the sense of self also arises and passes away.

296
00:45:34,494 --> 00:45:35,795
It's a choiceless awareness.

297
00:45:36,856 --> 00:45:43,588
It doesn't choose what to observe, it just sits back as if in a cinema and just watches the show.

298
00:45:44,092 --> 00:45:51,380
It wants to understand the body, heart and mind as they really are, not as it would wish them to be, or thought they were.

299
00:45:51,420 --> 00:45:57,547
To do this, sati is an impartial observation.

300
00:45:58,288 --> 00:46:01,150
It's not their judging, questioning, taking sides.

301
00:46:01,692 --> 00:46:02,713
It's not partisan.

302
00:46:03,474 --> 00:46:06,536
It's not coming from a fixed position, a view, an opinion.

303
00:46:07,478 --> 00:46:09,340
It's not biased or prejudiced.

304
00:46:10,400 --> 00:46:18,652
And when consciousness can so lift itself out of the morass of the psychophysical organism, it sets something free within itself.

305
00:46:19,894 --> 00:46:21,617
That enormous intelligence.

306
00:46:22,599 --> 00:46:28,847
The intuitive intelligence which we all have and which will lead itself eventually out of all suffering.

307
00:46:29,809 --> 00:46:33,235
This intelligence isn't to be confused with cleverness.

308
00:46:34,193 --> 00:46:36,478
The cleverest are sometimes quite unwise.

309
00:46:37,400 --> 00:46:39,163
This intelligence is intuitive.

310
00:46:39,364 --> 00:46:41,648
It sees or it doesn't see.

311
00:46:42,168 --> 00:46:42,951
It is immediate.

312
00:46:43,572 --> 00:46:47,400
Words, concepts, emotions, moods, all distort its vision.

313
00:46:48,101 --> 00:46:55,797
That's why the purification of the heart and mind has to go hand in hand with the process of enlightenment.

314
00:46:57,025 --> 00:47:02,190
It is this power of panya, intuitive intelligence, that sees things as they really are.

315
00:47:03,371 --> 00:47:12,501
And it does it in an environment of sati, awareness, which paradoxically fully experiences every physical, emotional and mental event.

316
00:47:14,161 --> 00:47:23,791
It would be logical to think that if we detach ourselves from our emotions, looked at them as it were from a distance, that we wouldn't be able to feel them so much.

317
00:47:24,025 --> 00:47:34,434
But to our surprise, when we set ourselves in the mode of satipanya, we feel emotions, sensations and no thoughts in a very direct, intimate way.

318
00:47:34,474 --> 00:47:42,882
It's a general experience of the newcomer to vipassana that they suddenly experience the sense bases more keenly.

319
00:47:43,663 --> 00:47:46,244
Suddenly the sky really is blue.

320
00:47:46,284 --> 00:47:52,311
One meditator said it was the first time they'd ever really tasted potatoes.

321
00:47:53,371 --> 00:48:00,617
and how strong our emotional life is felt, and how we become aware of the chattering masses in our own mind.

322
00:48:03,039 --> 00:48:16,052
What the Buddha discovered then was the awakening role of pure consciousness, its ability to free itself from the body, heart and mind, once it could perch itself firmly onto the post of observation.

323
00:48:17,532 --> 00:48:22,617
And he came to see that this samasati, this right awareness, was a controlling factor,

324
00:48:23,644 --> 00:48:26,548
It acted like the lead goose in a flight of geese.

325
00:48:28,112 --> 00:48:30,074
As it soared ahead, so the others followed.

326
00:48:31,257 --> 00:48:34,081
Right on its flanks flew interest and tranquility.

327
00:48:34,802 --> 00:48:37,947
They were further supported by right concentration and effort.

328
00:48:39,007 --> 00:48:42,193
And right behind awareness sits intuitive intelligence.

329
00:48:42,409 --> 00:48:46,717
itself supported by faith on the one flank and equanimity on the other.

330
00:48:47,898 --> 00:48:53,809
At any moment, this intelligence panya can dart forth, as it were, and take a momentary lead.

331
00:48:55,070 --> 00:49:03,304
That ability to intuit the way things really are is always there as potential whenever right awareness is established.

332
00:49:06,001 --> 00:49:18,579
So now, having gone through all the five indriya, the spiritual faculties, and the seven bhojanga, the factors of enlightenment, we've come to a point where we realize it was all unnecessary.

333
00:49:20,222 --> 00:49:25,449
All we have to do is establish right awareness and everything follows suit.

334
00:49:26,710 --> 00:49:32,920
The Buddha says it is enough to establish just that mindfulness so that direct insight can arise.

335
00:49:34,351 --> 00:49:40,567
So in a sense we can forget virtually everything I've just said and I feel a little embarrassed having wasted your time.

336
00:49:43,173 --> 00:49:45,199
We can of course use this knowledge skillfully.

337
00:49:45,860 --> 00:49:50,351
We should eventually be able to pinpoint whatever imbalance there is in our meditation.

338
00:49:51,461 --> 00:50:01,496
It may be one of the hindrances, but it could also be that there's just not enough effort, not enough concentration, too much effort, too much concentration, and so on.

339
00:50:01,516 --> 00:50:04,260
And here we would try to address the imbalance.

340
00:50:06,302 --> 00:50:13,932
This is all part of learning how to meditate, how to become more skillful in maintaining moment-to-moment mindfulness.

341
00:50:16,996 --> 00:50:18,498
So let's pause here for a moment.

342
00:50:48,516 --> 00:51:02,797
One of the teachers in the order I belong to, who was the chief monk at the Lanka Meditation Centre in Colombo, and now has a park-like monastery near Kandaboda, which is the meditation centre I stayed in, once gave me this apt metaphor.

343
00:51:03,759 --> 00:51:16,498
He said that awareness was like a dewdrop on the end of a leaf, and the sun couldn't shine through it because it was all murky with dust, the dust it had collected while rolling down that leaf.

344
00:51:17,947 --> 00:51:22,715
If all the dirt could be removed, then the sun would shine through brightly.

345
00:51:24,038 --> 00:51:28,485
The dewdrop is, of course, our awareness and the sun, nibbana.

346
00:51:31,070 --> 00:51:39,766
So our job is to purify awareness and this is done by simply observing whatever arises within the field of that awareness.

347
00:51:40,246 --> 00:51:41,068
How simple!

348
00:51:41,739 --> 00:51:45,353
Now I say simple, but we discover it's no easy thing to do.

349
00:51:45,393 --> 00:51:49,708
And that's why we've all come here for a week of hard sweatshop.

350
00:51:51,106 --> 00:51:59,697
to labour unceasingly at removing the dross, the accumulations of, dare we believe it, lifetimes of unskilful behaviour.

351
00:52:00,800 --> 00:52:02,081
But all is not darkness.

352
00:52:02,742 --> 00:52:12,496
We do have good qualities, wonderful qualities, and it's these we are developing at enormous speed when we undergo a special training like this.

353
00:52:13,396 --> 00:52:15,239
So take heart.

354
00:52:15,219 --> 00:52:18,505
The path is long, but there are many delights on the way.

355
00:52:19,067 --> 00:52:23,373
For instance, think of the ecstasy you'll feel when this course is over.

356
00:52:26,480 --> 00:52:31,568
Remember Socrates, the unexamined life is not worth living.

357
00:52:32,891 --> 00:52:36,637
Here's the Buddha from the Dhammapada, a collection of sayings.

358
00:52:38,204 --> 00:52:42,588
Only foolish and ignorant people indulge mindlessness.

359
00:52:43,489 --> 00:52:48,737
The wise guard their mindfulness as the greatest of all treasures.

360
00:52:50,958 --> 00:52:59,389
May your unflagging devotion to the development of all the faculties and factors of enlightenment bear great fruit.

361
00:53:00,371 --> 00:53:05,476
May you be fully awakened sooner rather than later.
